          "type": "text",
          "text": "Circuit built successfully! ✅ Here's the full breakdown:\n\n---\n\n## 🔌 Wiring Table\n\n| Arduino Pin | Wire Color | Component | Role |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **D12** | Red | LED1 (Red) Anode | LED1 output |\n| GND | Black | R1 (220Ω) → LED1 Cathode | LED1 current limit |\n| **D13** | Green | LED2 (Green) Anode | LED2 output |\n| GND | Black | R2 (220Ω) → LED2 Cathode | LED2 current limit |\n| **5V** | Red | BTN1 Pin 1 | Button power rail |\n| **D2** | Yellow | BTN1 Pin 2 (signal out) | Button input |\n| **D2** | Yellow | R3 (10kΩ) Pin 1 | Pull-down tie point |\n| **GND** | Black | R3 (10kΩ) Pin 2 | Pull-down to ground |\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Power Budget Summary\n\n| Pin | Load | Current | Safe? |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| D12 | LED1 + R1 (220Ω) | (5V−2V)/220Ω ≈ **~13.6 mA** | ✅ < 20mA |\n| D13 | LED2 + R2 (220Ω) | (5V−2V)/220Ω ≈ **~13.6 mA** | ✅ < 20mA |\n| D2 | Button + 10kΩ pull-down | 5V/10kΩ ≈ **~0.5 mA** | ✅ negligible |\n| **Total Board** | All active loads | **~27.7 mA** | ✅ well under 200mA Uno limit |\n\n> 🟢 All per-pin currents are safely below the 20mA limit. Total draw is well within the Arduino Uno's 200mA USB power budget.\n\n---\n\n## 🎮 Sketch Behavior\n\n| Condition | LED1 (Red) | LED2 (Green) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Button released** | Alternating blink (400ms each) | Alternating blink (400ms each) |\n| **Button pressed** | 💡 ON (solid) | 💡 ON (solid) |\n\n- The **10kΩ pull-down** on D2 ensures a clean `LOW` when the button is not pressed — no floating pin issues.\n- Serial monitor (`9600 baud`) prints state changes for easy debugging."
        }
      ]
    }
